	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>‘Oversupply’ on Senegalese onion markets sees prices plummet</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports suggest that there has been overproduction of onions in Senegal: ‘the production of onions in Senegal has risen from 120,000 to 200,000 tons per year’, while prices have fallen from €3.71/kg to €1.86/kg, a decrease of 50%. The government has appointed an ‘inter professional commission’ to look at the problems currently faced in the onion sector. This will include a review of export opportunities, with as currently in the EU only Spain imports onions from Senegal.</p><p>In Europe, a debate is under way on the state of the Dutch onion export trade. Industry sources report a 20% decline in Dutch onion exports in the first semester of 2011 compared to 2010, largely attributed to a 27% decline in exports to Russia. This occurred despite a shortfall in domestic Russian onion production as a result of bad weather, which led to high onion prices. The EU onion export trade to Russia has reportedly been subject to considerable seasonal variation. Exports to Senegal and Côte d’Ivoire meanwhile were reported as ‘still very slow in June compared to last year’.</p><p>In the longer term, it is thought that Dutch onion exports will continue to increase. In the last 30 years Dutch onion export capacity has more than tripled, according to Jaap Wiskerke of Wiskerke Onions. Mr Wiskerke maintains that ‘climate problems in the world have caused high prices for onions during the last three years’. However, the costs of shipping from Rotterdam to destinations such as Brazil is less than $0.06 per kg, and these low shipping costs are seen as providing the Dutch industry with a major advantage in delivering onions to coastal markets along the Atlantic seaboard.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Freshplaza.com</i>, ‘Overproduction of onions in Senegal’, 17 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84249" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84249</a></p><p><i>Productschap Tuinbouw</i>, ‘Dutch onion export notes 20% decrease in first half 2011’ 24 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84623" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84623</a></p><p><i>Freshplaza.com</i>, ‘14% drop of Russia's onion imports in 2010/11’, 25 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84660" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84660</a></p><p>Wiskerke Onions, ‘Dutch onion export will continue to increase’, 17 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84255" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=84255</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The very slow sales of onions on the Senegalese and Côte d’Ivoire markets in June, reported by Dutch onion exporters, is in large attributable to the import ban that operates in Senegal for the period from 1 April to 31 August.</p><p>In Senegal, there are disagreements over what the current market situation means. Some government officials take the view that the increase in production is indicative of the success of the seasonal import restrictions placed on onions from April to the end of August in recent years. Onion producers however take a different view, maintaining that the use of seasonal import restrictions encourages importers to stockpile onions before the closed period, and then to release these onions onto the market from April to August. It is this phenomenon, according to onion producers, that is leading to depressed onion prices.</p><p>It is apparent that the operation of the Senegalese onion market is not allowing production to expand at remunerative prices, and measures are clearly needed to strengthen the marketing of onions nationally and regionally, so that local onion producers can receive a realistic price for their produce. The market information systems and dialogue between professional organisations established in Namibia, alongside the use of import licences to strengthen the functioning of local supply chains, could well hold important lessons for the Senegalese onion sector.</p>
		</div>
		
